# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: covid-19-pandemic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:covid-19-pandemic/12th-state-council-of-china] The **12th State Council of China** lasted from March 2013 to March 2018, under the Li Keqiang premiership.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/12th-state-council-of-china] Premier Li was ranked only second to CCP general secretary Xi Jinping among 7 members of the 18th and 19th Politburo Standing Committee, top decision-making body of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/12th-state-council-of-china] During the 1st Session of the 12th National People's Congress in March 2013, Li Keqiang was appointed by new President Xi Jinping to replace Wen Jiabao as Premier of the State Council, China's head of government, according to the approval of the National People's Congress.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/12th-state-council-of-china] Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Macao Special Administrative Region (中央人民政府驻澳门特别行政区联络办公室), established on 18 January 2000.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/13th-state-council-of-china] The **13th State Council of China** lasted from March 2018 to March 2023, under the Li Keqiang premiership.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/13th-state-council-of-china] Premier Li was ranked only second to CCP general secretary Xi Jinping among 7 members of the 19th Politburo Standing Committee, top decision-making body of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/13th-state-council-of-china] During the 1st Session of the 13th National People's Congress in March 2018, Li Keqiang was appointed by President Xi according to the approval of the National People's Congress to re-serve as the Premier.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/13th-state-council-of-china] Develop & reform, institutional reform, etc.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/14th-state-council-of-china] The **Li Qiang government** is the 14th and current State Council of China since March 2023, under the Li Qiang premiership.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/14th-state-council-of-china] Premier Li is ranked only second to General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party Xi Jinping among 7 members of the 20th Politburo Standing Committee, the top decision-making body of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/14th-state-council-of-china] During the 1st Session of the 14th National People's Congress in March 2023, Li Qiang was appointed by President Xi Jinping to replace Li Keqiang as Premier of the State Council, China's head of government, according to the approval of the National People's Congress.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/14th-state-council-of-china] According to the constitution of China, the President nominates the Premier of the State Council, and the Premier nominates the Vice-Premiers, State Councilors and Ministers.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/14th-state-council-of-china] The nominations were approved by National People's Congress voting.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] In 1510, an acute respiratory disease emerged in Asia before spreading through North Africa and Europe during the first chronicled, inter-regional flu pandemic generally recognized by medical historians and epidemiologists.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Influenza-like illnesses had been documented in Europe since at least Charlemagne, with 1357's outbreak the first to be called *influenza*, but the 1510 flu pandemic is the first to be pathologically described following communication advances brought about by the printing press.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Flu became more widely referred to as *coqueluche* and *coccolucio* in France and Sicily during this pandemic, variations of which became the most popular names for flu in early modern Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The pandemic caused significant disruption in government, church, and society with near-universal infection and a mortality rate of around 1%.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The 1510 flu is suspected of originating in East Asia, possibly China.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Gregor Horst writes in *Operum medicorum tombus primus* (1661) that the disease came from Asia and spread along trade routes before attacking the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] German medical writer Justus Hecker suggested the 1510 influenza most likely came from Asia because of the historical nature of other influenzas to originate there in more recent pandemics.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] It is generally understood that the 1510 influenza had spread in Africa before Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Influenza was likely widespread in North Africa before crossing continents through the Mediterranean, arriving in Malta where British medical historian Thomas Short believed that the "island of *Melite* in *Africa*" became the 1510 flu's springboard into Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Europe's internationally traveled cities and flu's highly contagious nature enabled its spread through European populations.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The 1510 flu disrupted royal courts, church services, and social life across Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Contemporary chroniclers and those who have read their accounts observed how entire populations were attacked at once, which is how the disease first received the name *influenza* (from the belief that such outbreaks were caused by influences like stars or cold).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Turin professor Francisco Vallerioli (aka Valleriola) writes that the 1510 flu featured "Constriction of breathing, and beginning with a hoarseness of voice and... shivering.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Not long after that there being a cooked humor which fills the lungs." Physicians like Valleriola described the 1510 flu as more fatal to children and those who were bled.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Lawyer Francesco Muralto noted that "the disease killed 10 people out of a thousand in one day," supporting a fatality rate of around 1%.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The first cases of influenza began to appear in Sicily around July after the arrival of infected merchant ships from Malta.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] In Sicily it was commonly called *coccolucio* for the hood (resembling a coqueluchon - a kind of monk's cowl) the sick often wore over their heads.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Influenza quickly spread out along the Mediterranean coasts of Italy and southern France via merchant ships leaving the island.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Pope Julius II attributed the outbreaks in Rome and the Holy See to God's wrath.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Flu spread over the Alps into Switzerland and the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] In Switzerland it is documented as being called *das Gruppie* by the Mellingen chronicler Anton Tegenfeld, the flu nickname then preferred by German-speaking Europeans.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] A respiratory illness seemed to have menaced the Canton of Aargua in June, with the population falling ill with sniffling, coughing, and fatigue.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] André de Burgo's letters dated 24 August 1510 indicate Margaret of Austria had to intervene at a royal assembly between her father, Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian I, and Louis XII of France because the King of France was too sick with "coqueluche" to be spoken to.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Influenza spread out from the Holy Roman Empire towards Northern Europe, the Baltic states, and west towards France and England.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Arriving aboard infected sailors from Sicily, influenza struck the Kingdom of France through the ports of Marseille and Nice and spread through the international crowds of the shipyards.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Merchants, pilgrims, and other travelers from the south and east spread the virus throughout the western Mediterranean in July.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] It was referred to as "cephalie catarrhal" among French physicians, but more commonly just called **coqueluche**.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Historian François Eudes de Mézeray traced the etymology of "coqueluche" to an outbreak during the 1410s during which sufferers wore hoods resembling coqueluchons, a kind of monk's cowl.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] French surgeon Ambroise Paré described the outbreak as having been a "rheumatic affliction of the head...with constriction of the heart and lungs." By August it had appeared in Tours and after it had propagated itself throughout France over summer, sickening the entire country by September.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Coqueluche filled up the hospitals in France.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] King Louis XII's National Assembly of Bishops, Prelates, and university professors scheduled for September 1510 was delayed because of the intensity of the flu in Paris.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Jean Fernel (aka Fernelius), physician to Henry III of France, compares the 1557 influenza to the 1510 epidemic which attacked everyone with fever, a heaviness in their head, and profound coughing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Up to 1000 Parisians per day were dying at the height of the "1510 peste." Mézeray mentions that it disrupted judicial proceedings and colleges, and that the 1510 flu was more widespread and deadly in France than in other countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Cardinal Georges d'Amboise, a close friend and advisor to the King of France, is sometimes believed to have died of influenza since his health sharply declined after arriving in Lyons in May 1510.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The cardinal, also known as Monseigneur le Ledat, made his final testimony and recited Sacraments around 22 May before he died on the 25th.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] His sudden decline in health and flu's arrival in Europe around early summer have created uncertainty as to whether he died of gout or influenza, but "coqueluche" is not mentioned in French royal correspondence that year until August.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] British medical historian Charles Creighton claimed there is one foreign account of the 1510 flu in England, but did not elaborate.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Fernel and Paré suggested that the 1510 influenza "spread to almost all countries of the world" (not concerning Spain's territories in the New World).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] An epidemiological study of past influenza pandemics reviewing previous medical historians' data has found England was affected in 1510 and there were reports of symptoms like "gastrodynia" and noteworthy murrain among cattle.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The 1510 flu is also recorded to have reached Ireland.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Influenza reached the Iberian Peninsula early after Italy, due to the highly interconnected trade and pilgrimage routes between Spain, Portugal, and the Italian kingdoms.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Cases began to appear in Portugal around the same time the disease entered the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Spanish cities were reportedly "dispopulated" by the 1510 flu.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] There are no records of influenza affecting the New World in 1510, even though Spain was sending fleets of ships across the Atlantic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The first recorded flu outbreak in the New World had afflicted the Isle of Santo Domingo (Now Haiti and the Dominican Republic) in 1493.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Blistering on the back of the head and shoulders was one form of treatment prescribed in Europe for the flu.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Paré regarded the common treatments of bloodletting and purgation to be especially dangerous to 1510's flu patients.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Supraorbital pain and vision problems were symptoms of *coqueluche*, so sufferers may have felt tempted to wear hoods due to light sensitivity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Justus Hecker and John Parkin presumed the 1510 influenza originated from East Asia because of the historical nature of other influenza pandemics to originate there, while in 1661 Gregor Horst wrote that the 1510 flu spread along trade routes from East Asia to Africa before reaching Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Influenza viruses sometimes leap from Asia's migratory water fowl after massive migrations congregate near water sources for humans and domesticated animals, in which cross-species infections trigger antigenic shift and create new strains of flu human beings have little immunity to.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The 1510 "coqueluche" has been recognized as influenza by modern epidemiologists and medical historians.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] Adults with pertussis will usually cough for weeks before becoming gradually more ill then recovering over a period of months.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The *coqueluche* of 1510 is considered to be influenza by experts because of its sudden symptoms, explosive spread, and timelines of sickness to recovery.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1510-influenza-pandemic] The first outbreak of whooping cough to be agreed on by most medical historians is Guillaume de Baillou's description of an outbreak in Paris in 1578.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In 1557, a pandemic strain of influenza emerged in Asia, then spread to Africa, Europe, and eventually the Americas.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] This flu was highly infectious and presented with intense, occasionally lethal symptoms.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Medical historians like Thomas Short, Lazare Rivière and Charles Creighton gathered descriptions of catarrhal fevers recognized as influenza by modern physicians attacking populations with the greatest intensity between 1557 and 1559.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The 1557 flu saw governments, for possibly the first time, inviting physicians to instill bureaucratic organization into epidemic responses.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] It is also the first pandemic where influenza is pathologically linked to miscarriages, given its first English names, and is reliably recorded as having spread globally.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza caused higher burial rates, near-universal infection, and economic turmoil as it returned in repeated waves.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] According to a European chronicler surnamed Fonseca who wrote *Disputat. de Garotillo,* the 1557 influenza pandemic first broke out in Asia.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The flu spread west along established trade and pilgrimage routes before reaching the Ottoman Empire and the Middle East.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] An epidemic of a flu-like illness is recorded for September 1557 in Portuguese Goa.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In the summer of 1557 parts of Europe had just suffered outbreaks of plague, typhus, measles, and smallpox when influenza arrived from the Ottoman Empire and North Africa.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The flu spread west through Europe aboard merchant ships in the Mediterranean Sea, again taking advantage of trade and pilgrimage routes.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Death rates were highest in children, those with preexisting conditions, the elderly, and those who were bled.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Outbreaks were particularly severe in communities suffering from food scarcity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The epidemics of fevers and respiratory illness eventually became referred to as the **new sickness** in England, **new acquaintance** in Scotland, and **coqueluche** or simply **catarrh** by medical historians in the rest of Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Because it afflicted entire populations at once in mass outbreaks, some contemporary scholars thought the flu was caused by stars, contaminated vapors brought about by damp weather, or the dryness of the air.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Ultimately the 1557 flu lasted in varying waves of intensity for around four years in epidemics that increased European death rates, disrupted the highest levels of society, and frequently spread to other continents.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The flu pandemic first reached Europe in 1557 from the Ottoman Empire along trade and shipping routes connected to Constantinople, brought to Asia Minor by infected travelers from the Middle East.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] At the time, the Ottoman Empire's territory included most of the Balkans and Bulgaria.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] This gave influenza unrestricted access to Athens, Sofia, and Sarajevo as it spread throughout the empire.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza set sail from the capital, Constantinople, into the recently conquered North African territories of Tripoli (1551) and the Habesh (1557), from where it likely ricocheted to Malta from North Africa via merchant ships, as during the pandemic of 1510.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] On land, influenza spread north from the Ottoman Empire over Wallachia to the Kingdom of Poland and Grand Duchy of Lithuania before moving west into continental Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza arrived in the Kingdom of Sicily in June at Palermo, whence it spread across the island.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Church services, Sicilian social life, and the economy were disrupted as the flu sickened a large portion of the population.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The Sicilian Senate asked a well-known Palermitan physician named Giovanni Filippo Ingrassia to help combat the epidemic in an advisory capacity, which he accepted.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Ingrassia approached epidemic responses as a collaboration between healthcare and government officials, and was the first known "health care professional" to propose that a system for monitoring epidemics of contagious catarrhal fevers would aid in early detection and epidemic control.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Flu spread quickly from Sicily into the Kingdom of Naples on the lower part of the Italian Peninsula, moving upward along the coastline.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In Urbino, Venetian court poet Bernardo Tasso, his son Torquato, and the occupants of a monastery fell sick "from hand to hand" with influenza for four to five days.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Though the epidemic left the entire city of Urbino ill, most individuals recovered without complications.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] By the time Bernardo had traveled to northern Italy on August 3 the disease had already spread into the rest of Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In Lombardy there was an outbreak of "suffocating catarrh" that could quickly become fatal.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The symptoms were so severe that some members of the population suspected a mass poisoning had occurred.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Padua began to see cases in August, with sickness lasting into September.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] German medical historian Justus Hecker writes that the young population of Padua had been reeling from a dual outbreak of measles and smallpox since the spring when a new illness, featuring extreme cough and headache, began to afflict the citizens in late summer.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The illness was referred to as *coqueluche.* Switzerland was also reached by the disease in August.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] "Catarrh" swept through the Swiss plateaus from August to September and almost disrupted the graduate studies of Swiss physician Felix Plater, who was sickened by severe fits of coughing while a candidate for his doctorate.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] French physician and medical historian Lazare Rivière documented an anonymous physician's descriptions of a flu outbreak occurring in the Languedoc region of France in July 1557.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The disease, often called *coqueluche* by the French, caused a severe outbreak in Nîmes that featured a fast onset of symptoms like headaches, fevers, loss of appetite, fatigue, and intense coughing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Most of those who died from the disease did so on the fourth day, but some succumbed up to 11 days after first symptoms.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Across Languedoc influenza had a high mortality rate, with up to 200 people per day dying in Toulouse at the height of the region's epidemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Italian physician Francisco Vallerioli, known as François Valleriola, was a witness to the epidemic in France and described the 1557 flu's symptoms as featuring a fever, severe headache, intense coughing, shortness of breath, chills, hoarseness, and expulsion of phlegm after 7 to 14 days.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] French lawyer Étienne Pasquier wrote that the disease began with a severe pain in the head and a 12- to 15-hour fever while sufferers' noses "ran like a fountain." Paris saw its judiciary disrupted when the Paris Law Court suspended its meetings to slow the spread of flu.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Medical historian Charles-Jacques Saillant described this influenza as especially fatal to those who were treated with bleeding and very dangerous to children.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The 1557 influenza severely impacted the British Isles.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Short found that the number of burials for market towns was much higher than christenings from 1557 to 1562.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] For example, the annual number of burials in Tonbridge increased from 33 on average in 1556 to 61 in 1557, 105 in 1558, and 94 in 1559.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Before the flu epidemic, England had suffered from a poor harvest and widespread famine that medical historian Thomas Short believed made the epidemic more deadly.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Contemporary historian John Stow wrote that during "winter the quarterne agues continued in like manner" to 1557's epidemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] On 6 September 1558 the Governor of the Isle of Wight, Lord St.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] John, wrote in a despatch to Mary I of England about a highly-contagious illness afflicting more than half the people of Southampton, the Isle of Wight, and Portsmouth (places where Lord St.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] He has had four sore fits, and is brought very low, and in danger of his life if they continue as they have done." Influenza began to move north through England, felling numerous farmers and leaving large quantities of grain unharvested before it reached London around mid-late October.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Queen Mary and Archbishop of Canterbury Reginald Pole, who had both been in poor health before flu broke out in London, likely died of influenza within 12 hours of each other on 17 November 1558.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Ultimately around 8000 other Londoners likely died of influenza during the epidemic, including many elders and parish priests.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] New waves of "agues" and fevers were recorded in England into 1559.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] These repeated outbreaks proved unusually deadly for populations already suffering from extensive rains and poor harvests.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] From 1557 to 1559 the nation's population contracted by 2%.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The sheer numbers of people dying from epidemics and famine in England caused economic inflation to flatten out.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In the late 1550s the English language had not yet developed a proper name for the flu, despite previous epidemics.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Thus 1557's epidemic was either described as a "plague" (like many epidemics with notable mortality), "ague" (most generally) or "new disease" in England.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] "The sweat" was one name used to describe the usually deadly, flu-like fevers and "agues" plaguing the English countryside from 1557 to 1558, despite no reliable records of sweating sickness after 1551.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Doctor John Jones, a prominent 16th Century London physician, refers in his book *Dyall of Agues* to a "great sweat" during the reign of Mary I of England.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] After the 1557 pandemic English nicknames for the flu began to appear in letters, like "the new disease" in England and "the newe acquaintance" in Scotland.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Habsburg Netherlands was also heavily impacted by the flu in October.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Dutch historian Petrus Forestus described an outbreak in Alkmaar where 2000 fell sick with flu and 200 perished in a span of three weeks.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Forestus himself became sick with the flu and related that it "...began with a slight fever like a common catarrh, and showed its great malignancy only by degrees.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Sudden fits of suffocation then came on, and the pain of the chest was so distressing that patients imagined they must die in the paroxysm.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The complaint was increased still by a tight, convulsive cough.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Death did not take place till the 9th or 14th day." He further observed that the flu was very dangerous to pregnant women, killing at least eight such citizens in Alkmaar who contracted it.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza's symptoms came on suddenly and attacked thousands of the city's residents at the same time.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Hunger likely contributed to a higher death toll, as the authorities had been struggling to provide food to the needy amid a severe bread shortage during the summer.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Attempting to explain the epidemic of fevers and respiratory illness affecting the Low Countries, Flemish physician Rembert Dodoens suggested that the mass outbreaks of illness were caused by a dry, hot summer following a very cold winter.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Spain was widely and severely impacted by influenza, which chroniclers recognized as a highly contagious catarrhal fever.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza likely arrived in Spain around July, with the first cases being reported near Madrid in August.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] British medical historian Thomas Short wrote that "At Mantua Carpentaria, three miles outside of Madrid, the first cases were reported...There it began with a roughness of the jaws, small cough, then a strong fever with a pain in the head, back, and legs.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Some felt as though they were corded over the breast, with a weight at the stomach, all which continued to the third day at the furthest.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Then the fever went off, with a sweat of bleeding at the nose.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Cases expanded exponentially as merchants, pilgrims, and other travelers leaving Madrid transported the virus to cities and towns across the country.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] According to King Phillip II's doctor Luis de Mercado, "All the population was attacked the same day, and the same time of day.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] It was catarrh, marked by fever of the double tertian type, with such pernicious symptoms that many died." The season's poor harvests and hunger in the Spanish population, as well as negligent medical care, likely contributed to the severity of the influenza pandemic in Spain.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Flu symptoms could be so intense that the region's physicians often distinguished it from other contagious, seasonal pneumonias that spread from East Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza hit the Kingdom of Portugal at the same time as it spread throughout Spain, with an impact that spread across the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The kingdom had just suffered food shortages due to 1556–57's poor harvest, which would have exacerbated the effects of the flu on hungry patients.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] A violent storm had just hit Portugal and severely damaged the Palace of Enxobregas, and in following with attributing outbreaks of influenza to the weather Portuguese historians like Ignácio Barbosa-Machado attributed the epidemic in the kingdom to the storm with little opposition.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] There are records of the New World eventually being reached by the flu in 1557, brought to the Spanish and Portuguese Empires by sailors from Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza arrived in Central America in 1557, likely aboard Spanish ships sailing to New Spain.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] During that year there were epidemics of flu recorded in the south Atlantic states, Gulf area, and Southwest.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The Native American Cherokee appear to have been affected during this wave, and it may have spread along newly established trade routes between Spanish colonies in the New World.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Dobyns described a 1557 epidemic of influenza in Ecuador in which European and Native populations were both left sick with severe coughing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In Colonial Brazil, Portuguese missionaries did not take breaks from religious activities when they became sick.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Missionaries like the Society of Jesus in Brazil founder Manuel da Nóbrega continued to preach, host mass, and baptize converts in the New World even when symptomatic with contagious illnesses like influenza.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] As a result, flu would have quickly spread through Portuguese colonies due to mandatory church attendance.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Baptism rates in native communities were deeply connected with outbreaks of disease, and missionary policies of conducting religious activities while sick likely helped spread the flu.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Influenza attacked Africa through the Ottoman Empire, which by 1557 was expanding its territories in the northern and eastern parts of the continent.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Egypt, which had been conquered by the Ottoman Empire around 40 years prior, became an access point for influenza to travel south through the Red Sea along shipping routes.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The pandemic's most memorable effects on the Ottoman army in Africa are recorded as part of the 1559 wave.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The Kingdom of Portugal had supported the Abyssinian (Ethiopian) Empire in their war against the Ottoman expansion of the Habesh Eyalet and sent aid to their emperor, including a team with Andrés de Oviedo in 1557 who recorded the events.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In 1559 the Ottoman Empire struggled with a severe wave of influenza: After the deaths of Emperor Gelawdewos and most of the Portuguese attaché in battle, the flu killed thousands of the Ottoman army's troops occupying the port city of Massawa.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Massawa was claimed by the Ottomans from Medri Bahri during their conquest of Habesh in 1557, but the pandemic's 1559 wave challenged their army's hold onto territory around the city after flu cut down a large number of the Ottoman forces.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Because of the epidemic Ottoman soldiers were soon recalled back to the ports, even though the emperor had been slain, and shortly afterwards Gelawdewos's brother Menas ascended to the Abyssinian throne and converted from Islam to Christianity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Most physicians of the time subscribed to the theory of humorism, and believed the cosmos or climate directly affected the health of entire communities.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Physicians treating the flu often used treatments called coctions to remove excess humors they believed to be causing illness.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] In Urbino, "diet and good governance" were recognized as common ways sufferers managed their illness.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] The 1557 pandemic's nature as a worldwide, highly-contagious respiratory disease with fast onset of flu-like symptoms has led many physicians, from medical historians like Charles Creighton to modern epidemiologists, to consider the causative disease as influenza.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] "Well documented descriptions from medical observers" who witnessed the effects of the pandemic as it spread through populations have been reviewed by numerous medical historians in the centuries since.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Contemporary physicians to the 1557 flu, like Ingrassia, Valleriola, Dodoens, and Mercado, described symptoms like severe coughing, fever, myalgia, and pneumonia that all occurred within a short period of time and led to death in days if a case was to be fatal.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Infections became so widespread in countries that influences like the weather, stars, and mass poisoning were blamed by observers for the outbreaks, a reoccurring pattern in influenza epidemics that has contributed to the disease's name.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] Prior to greater research being conducted into influenza in the 19th century, some medical historians considered the descriptions of epidemic "angina" from 1557 to be scarlet fever, whooping cough, and diphtheria.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] But the most striking features of scarlet fever and diphtheria, like rashes or pseudomembranes, remain unmentioned by any of the 1557 pandemic's observers and the first recognized whooping cough epidemic is a localized outbreak in Paris from 1578.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1557-influenza-pandemic] These illnesses can resemble the flu in their early stages but pandemic influenza is distinguished by its fast-moving, unrestricted epidemics of severe respiratory disease affecting all ages with widespread infections and mortalities.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] In 1563, London experienced its worst episode of plague during the sixteenth century.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] At least 20,136 people in London and surrounding parishes were recorded to have died of plague during the outbreak.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Around 24% of London's population ultimately perished, but the plague affected London's unsanitary parishes and neighbourhoods the most.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] In 1563 the City of London was overcrowded, unsanitary, and poorly-policed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Queen Elizabeth I reigned in her fifth year and the government struggled with a rapidly increasing population.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Although sanitation was a constant problem, the city had gone over a dozen years without a plague epidemic and many contemporary Londoners were unconcerned about the disease.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] That changed in 1563 when plague suddenly erupted in Derby, Leicester, and London with such virulence that sickness spread to English troops garrisoned at Havre, weakening them and causing a surrender to French forces.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] The first cases of plague began to appear in June.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] According to manuscripts by John Stow kept at Lambeth Library, weekly bills of mortality for 1563 show the first 17 recorded plague deaths for the week ending 12 June.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Elizabeth began coordinating a government response to the epidemic by communicating orders to her people through the Church.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Churchwardens and curates were instructed to tell parishioners staying with those sick with plague not to come to church until several weeks after they recover.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Strict countermeasures were taken at the local level to combat the epidemic, such as painting blue crosses on the houses of the infected and government orders to kill and bury all stray cats and dogs "for the avoidance of plague," with special officers appointed to carry out the cull.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Cases began to steadily increase over the next few weeks, with plague killing 131 Londoners for the week ending 3 July before sharply increasing to hundreds of deaths per week by 30 July.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Poulkar's was the most severely affected parish, having large quantities of fruit merchandise and filth in the lanes attracting rats.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Geynes, known for invoking Galen and being citationed by the government for it, died on 23 July from plague.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] John Jones, contracted plague after staying in the house of a sick person but survived the illness.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Jones promotes the theory of contagion in his *Dyall of Auges*, writing that "I myself was infected by reason that unawares I lodged with one who had it running from him." As London's death toll soared, fear of the plague became palpable in the Royal Court.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Elizabeth and the Royal Council decided to avoid the City of London entirely.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] The Queen moved the Royal Court to Windsor Castle and erected a gallows in the town square, threatening to hang anyone who followed them from London.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] She prudently banned the transportation of goods into Windsor from London, as she too had a fear of contagion.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] A pious queen, Elizabeth also wrote to Thomas Young, the Archbishop of York, to recommend universal prayer and fasting for hastening "remedy and mitigation" of the plague in her realm.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] An average of 1,449 people were dying weekly between 27 August and 1 October, peaking at 1,828 plague deaths in London for the week ending 1 October.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Queen Elizabeth's government gave new orders on 30 September that all houses with infected individuals should have their doors and windows boarded up and that no person inside shall make contact with persons outside for 40 days.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] This strict quarantine may have had an immediate effect, with plague deaths the next week dropping over 30% to 1,262 for the week ending 8 October.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] It is normal during plague outbreaks for the disease to subside or break in a community during the winter months, as rats and their fleas retreat from snow and their resources thin out.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] By 2 December deaths had fallen to 178 per week and the Common Council released an order that none of the houses where plague patients had been can be rented out.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1563-london-plague] Cases continued to decline to 13 deaths for the week ending 21 January 1564 before plague dissipated from the city.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] From 1592 to 1593, London experienced its last major plague outbreak of the 16th century.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] During this period, at least 15,000 people died of plague within the City of London and another 4,900 died of plague in the surrounding parishes.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] London in 1592 was a partially-walled city of 150,000 people made of the City of London and its surrounding parishes, called liberties, just outside the walls.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Queen Elizabeth I had ruled for 34 years and her government struggled with London's quickly growing population.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Due to increasing economic and food shortages, disorder had grown among the underclasses in the city and beyond, whom moralist authorities increasingly struggled to govern.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] A large and impoverished population made up the surrounding liberties, which became the first communities to be hit severely by the plague.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Plague had been present in England since the Black Death, infecting various fauna in the countryside, and known as plague since the 15th century.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Occasionally *Yersinia pestis* was transmitted to human society by infectious contact with the fleas of wild animals, with disastrous results for trade, farming, and social life.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Increasing plague activity along England's southern and eastern coasts appeared during the late 1580s and the early 1590s.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] An outbreak at Newcastle in 1589 killed 1727 residents by January 1590, while from 1590 to 1592 Plymouth and Devon were affected with 997 plague deaths at Totnes and Tiverton.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] London's first cases of plague were noticed in August.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] On 7 September, soldiers marching from England's north to embark on foreign campaigns were rerouted around the city due to concerns about infection, and by the 21st at least 35 parishes were infected with the plague.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] A group transporting the spoils of a Spanish carrack from Dartmouth couldn't get further than Greenwich due to the outbreak in London and news of the plague had spread regionally.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] London's theatres, which had been temporarily closed by city authorities since a riot in June, had their shutdown orders extended to 29 December by the government.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Members of the aristocratic class sensed danger as the disease continued to spread and fled the city: "The plague is so sore that none of worth stay about these places" remarked one contemporary.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] William Shakespeare, being among the plague refugees at this time, took the time to write his famed sonnets.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] In November, London's College of Physicians convened a meeting to discuss the "insolent and illicit practice" of London's unlicensed medical physicians with the intention to "summon them all" before the college for quackery.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Queen Elizabeth's royal court also decided not to host the annual Accession Day tilt celebrations for the month due to the possibility of contagion at the royal court.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Some records of the plague were copied by John Stow during his own research in the 17th century and have survived time despite the original documents being lost.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Around 2,000 Londoners died of plague between August 1592 and January 1593.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] The Company of Parish Clerks began regularly keeping and publishing records of plague mortality on 21 December 1592.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Government orders forbidding performances at theatres were again extended, into 1593.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Death and infection rates rose steadily during the winter months, even though low temperatures often slow down flea activity during plague epidemics.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] This was seen as ominous by Londoners observing the epidemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] More resourceful, upper-class individuals continued fleeing during 1593 as the government's countermeasures proved ineffective due to the disease-harboring conditions in some areas of London.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Poorer, unsanitary parishes and neighborhoods were located near the city wall and River Thames while the Fleet Ditch area of London, around Fleet Prison, became the most heavily infected part of the city.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] The city's sugar refineries continued their business unabated even though public houses and theatres remained closed on government orders to halt the spread of infection.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] Alarm was raised at Windsor by the death of Queen Elizabeth's chambermaid Lady Scrope from plague on 21 August within the castle, which almost sent the royal court fleeing a second time.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/1592-1593-london-plague] But the government remained at Windsor Castle through November where Queen Elizabeth hosted her tilt celebrations.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The global **COVID-19 pandemic** (also known as the **coronavirus pandemic**), caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), began with an outbreak in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It spread to other parts of Asia and then worldwide in early 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) declared the outbreak a public health emergency of international concern (PHEIC) on 30 January 2020 and assessed it as having become a pandemic on 11 March.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO declared that the public health emergency caused by COVID-19 had ended in May 2023, while noting that COVID-19 continued to be a global health threat.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] COVID-19 symptoms range from asymptomatic to deadly, but most commonly include fever, sore throat, nocturnal cough, and fatigue.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Transmission of the virus is often through airborne particles.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Mutations have produced many strains (variants) with varying degrees of infectivity and virulence.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] COVID-19 vaccines were developed rapidly and deployed to the general public beginning in December 2020, made available through government and international programmes such as COVAX, aiming to provide vaccine equity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Treatments include novel antiviral drugs and symptom control.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Common mitigation measures during the public health emergency included travel restrictions, lockdowns, business restrictions and closures, workplace hazard controls, mask mandates, quarantines, testing systems, and contact tracing of the infected.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic caused severe social and economic disruption around the world, including the largest global recession since the Great Depression.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Widespread supply shortages, including food shortages, were caused by supply chain disruptions and panic buying.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Reduced human activity led to an unprecedented temporary decrease in pollution.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Educational institutions and public areas were partially or fully closed in many jurisdictions, and many events were cancelled or postponed during 2020 and 2021.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Telework became much more common for white-collar workers as the pandemic evolved.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Misinformation circulated through social media and occasionally through mass media, and political tensions intensified.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic raised issues of racial and geographic discrimination, health equity, and the balance between public health imperatives and individual rights.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The disease has continued to circulate since 2023.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Different definitions of pandemics lead to different determinations of when they end.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 6 June 2026, COVID-19 has caused 7,114,321 confirmed deaths and 18.5 to 35.2 million estimated deaths.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic was the fifth-deadliest pandemic or epidemic in history.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In epidemiology, a pandemic is defined as "an epidemic occurring over a very wide area, crossing international boundaries, and usually affecting a large number of people".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, as with other pandemics, the meaning of this term has been challenged.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The end of a pandemic or other epidemic only rarely involves the total disappearance of a disease, and historically, much less attention has been given to defining the ends of epidemics than their beginnings.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The ends of particular epidemics have been defined in a variety of ways, differing according to academic field, and differently based on location and social group.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] An epidemic's end can be considered a social phenomenon, not just a biological one.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] During the initial outbreak in Wuhan, the virus and disease were commonly referred to as "coronavirus", "Wuhan coronavirus", "the coronavirus outbreak" and the "Wuhan coronavirus outbreak", with the disease sometimes called "Wuhan pneumonia".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In January 2020, the WHO recommended 2019-nCoV and 2019-nCoV acute respiratory disease as interim names for the virus and disease per 2015 international guidelines against using geographical locations (e.g.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Wuhan, China), animal species, or groups of people in disease and virus names in part to prevent social stigma.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO finalised the official names COVID-19 and SARS-CoV-2 on 11 February 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] WHO Director-General Tedros Ghebreyesus explained: CO for *corona*, VI for *virus*, D for *disease* and 19 for when the outbreak was first identified (31 December 2019).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO additionally uses "the COVID-19 virus" and "the virus responsible for COVID-19" in public communications.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO named variants of concern and variants of interest using Greek letters.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The initial practice of naming them according to where the variants were identified (e.g.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Delta began as the "Indian variant") is no longer common.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A more systematic naming scheme reflects the variant's PANGO lineage (e.g., Omicron's lineage is B.1.1.529) and is used for other variants.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] SARS-CoV-2 is a virus closely related to bat coronaviruses, pangolin coronaviruses, and SARS-CoV.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The first known outbreak (the 2019–2020 COVID-19 outbreak in mainland China) started in Wuhan, Hubei, China, in December 2019.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many early cases were linked to people who had visited the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market there, but it is possible that human-to-human transmission began earlier.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Molecular clock analysis suggests that the first cases were likely to have been between October and November 2019.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The scientific consensus is that the virus is most likely of a zoonotic origin, from bats or another closely related mammal.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] While other explanations, such as speculations that SARS-CoV-2 was accidentally released from a laboratory, have been proposed, as of 2021 these were not sufficiently supported by evidence.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official "case" counts refer to the number of people who have been tested for COVID-19 and whose test has been confirmed positive according to official protocols whether they experienced symptomatic disease.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Due to the effect of sampling bias, studies which obtain a more accurate number by extrapolating from a random sample have consistently found that total infections considerably exceed the reported case counts.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many countries, early on, had official policies to not test those with only mild symptoms.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The strongest risk factors for severe illness are obesity, complications of diabetes, anxiety disorders, and the total number of conditions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] During the start of the COVID-19 pandemic, it was not clear whether young people were less likely to be infected, or less likely to develop symptoms and be tested.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A retrospective cohort study in China found that children and adults were just as likely to be infected.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Among more thorough studies, preliminary results from 9 April 2020 found that in Gangelt, the centre of a major infection cluster in Germany, 15 per cent of a population sample tested positive for antibodies.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Screening for COVID-19 in pregnant women in New York City, and blood donors in the Netherlands, found rates of positive antibody tests that indicated more infections than reported.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Seroprevalence-based estimates are conservative as some studies show that persons with mild symptoms do not have detectable antibodies.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Initial estimates of the basic reproduction number (R0) for COVID-19 in January 2020 were between 1.4 and 2.5, but a subsequent analysis claimed that it may be about 5.7 (with a 95 per cent confidence interval of 3.8 to 8.9).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In December 2021, the number of cases continued to climb due to several factors, including new COVID-19 variants.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of that 28 December, 282,790,822 individuals worldwide had been confirmed as infected.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 14 April 2022, over 500 million cases were confirmed globally.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Most cases are unconfirmed, with the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimating the true number of cases as of early 2022 to be in the billions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] One measure that public health officials and policymakers have used to monitor the pandemic and guide decision-making is the test positivity rate ("percent positive").
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] According to Johns Hopkins in 2020, one benchmark for a "too high" per cent positive is 5%, which was used by the WHO in the past.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 10 March 2023, more than 6.88 million deaths had been attributed to COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The first confirmed death was in Wuhan on 9 January 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These numbers vary by region and over time, influenced by testing volume, healthcare system quality, treatment options, government response, time since the initial outbreak, and population characteristics, such as age, sex, and overall health.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Multiple measures are used to quantify mortality.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official death counts typically include people who died after testing positive.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Such counts exclude deaths without a test.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Conversely, deaths of people who died from underlying conditions following a positive test may be included.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Countries such as Belgium include deaths from suspected cases, including those without a test, thereby increasing counts.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official death counts have been claimed to underreport the actual death toll, because excess mortality (the number of deaths in a period compared to a long-term average) data show an increase in deaths that is not explained by COVID-19 deaths alone.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Such deaths include deaths due to healthcare capacity constraints and priorities, as well as reluctance to seek care (to avoid possible infection).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Further research may help distinguish the proportions directly caused by COVID-19 from those caused by indirect consequences of the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In May 2022, the WHO estimated the number of excess deaths by the end of 2021 to be 14.9 million compared to 5.4 million reported COVID-19 deaths, with the majority of the unreported 9.5 million deaths believed to be direct deaths due to the virus, rather than indirect deaths.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Some deaths were because people with other conditions could not access medical services.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A December 2022 WHO study estimated excess deaths from the pandemic during 2020 and 2021, again concluding ≈14.8 million excess early deaths occurred, reaffirming and detailing their prior calculations from May as well as updating them, addressing criticisms.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These numbers do not include measures like years of potential life lost and may make the pandemic 2021's leading cause of death.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The time between symptom onset and death ranges from 6 to 41 days, typically about 14 days.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Mortality rates increase as a function of age.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] People at the greatest mortality risk are the elderly and those with underlying conditions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The infection fatality ratio (IFR) is the cumulative number of deaths attributed to the disease divided by the cumulative number of infected individuals (including asymptomatic and undiagnosed infections and excluding vaccinated infected individuals).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Other studies refer to this metric as the *infection fatality risk*.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In November 2020, a review article in *Nature* reported estimates of population-weighted IFRs for various countries, excluding deaths in elderly care facilities, and found a median range of 0.24% to 1.49%.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These rates vary by a factor of ≈10,000 across the age groups.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] For comparison, the IFR for middle-aged adults is two orders of magnitude higher than the annualised risk of a fatal automobile accident and much higher than the risk of dying from seasonal influenza.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In December 2020, a systematic review and meta-analysis estimated that population-weighted IFR was 0.5% to 1% in some countries (France, Netherlands, New Zealand, and Portugal), 1% to 2% in other countries (Australia, England, Lithuania, and Spain), and about 2.5% in Italy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This study reported that most of the differences reflected corresponding differences in the population's age structure and the age-specific pattern of infections.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] There have also been reviews that have compared the fatality rate of this pandemic with prior pandemics, such as MERS-CoV.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] For comparison the infection mortality rate of seasonal flu in the United States is 0.1%, which is 13 times lower than COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Another metric in assessing death rate is the case fatality ratio (CFR), which is the ratio of deaths to diagnoses.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This metric can be misleading because of the delay between symptom onset and death and because testing focuses on symptomatic individuals.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Based on Johns Hopkins University statistics, the global CFR was 1.02 percent (6,881,955 deaths for 676,609,955 cases) as of 10 March 2023.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The number varies by region and has generally declined over time.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Several variants have been named by WHO and labelled as a variant of concern (VoC) or a variant of interest (VoI).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many of these variants have shared the more infectious D614G.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of May 2023, the WHO had downgraded all variants of concern to previously circulating as these were no longer detected in new infections.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Sub-lineages of the Omicron variant (BA.1 – BA.5) were considered separate VoCs by the WHO until they were downgraded in March 2023 as no longer widely circulating.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 24 September 2024, the variants of interest as specified by the WHO are BA.2.86 and JN.1, and the variants under monitoring are JN.1.7, KP.2, KP.3, KP.3.1.1, JN.1.18, LB.1, and XEC.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Symptoms of COVID-19 are variable, ranging from mild symptoms to severe illness.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Common symptoms include headache, loss of smell and taste, nasal congestion and runny nose, cough, muscle pain, sore throat, fever, diarrhoea, and breathing difficulties.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] People with the same infection may have different symptoms, and their symptoms may change over time.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In people without prior ear, nose, and throat disorders, loss of taste combined with loss of smell is associated with COVID-19 and is reported in as many as 88% of cases.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The disease is mainly transmitted via the respiratory route when people inhale droplets and small airborne particles (that form an aerosol) that infected people exhale as they breathe, talk, cough, sneeze, or sing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Infected people are more likely to transmit COVID-19 when they are physically close to other non-infected individuals.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] However, infection can occur over longer distances, particularly indoors.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] SARS‑CoV‑2 belongs to the broad family of viruses known as coronaviruses.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It is a positive-sense single-stranded RNA (+ssRNA) virus, with a single linear RNA segment.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Coronaviruses infect humans, other mammals, including livestock and companion animals, and avian species.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Human coronaviruses are capable of causing illnesses ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS, fatality rate ≈34%).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] SARS-CoV-2 is the seventh known coronavirus to infect people, after 229E, NL63, OC43, HKU1, MERS-CoV, and the original SARS-CoV.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The standard method of testing for presence of SARS-CoV-2 is a nucleic acid test, which detects the presence of viral RNA fragments.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As these tests detect RNA but not infectious virus, its "ability to determine duration of infectivity of patients is limited".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The test is typically done on respiratory samples obtained by a nasopharyngeal swab; however, a nasal swab or sputum sample may also be used.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO has published several testing protocols for the disease.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A COVID-19 vaccine is intended to provide acquired immunity against severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS‑CoV‑2), the virus that causes coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, an established body of knowledge existed about the structure and function of coronaviruses causing diseases like severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) and Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This knowledge accelerated the development of various vaccine platforms during early 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The initial focus of SARS-CoV-2 vaccines was on preventing symptomatic and severe illness.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The COVID-19 vaccines are widely credited for their role in reducing the severity and death caused by COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of August 2024, more than 5.6 billion people had received one or more doses (13.7 billion in total).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Oxford-AstraZeneca vaccine was the most widely used.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] According to a June 2022 study, COVID-19 vaccines prevented an additional 14.4 million to 19.8 million deaths in 185 countries and territories from 8 December 2020 to 8 December 2021.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In 2022, the first recombinant protein-based COVID-19 vaccine (the Novavax vaccine) was authorised for use in adults in the United Kingdom.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It has subsequently received endorsement/authorisation from the WHO, US, European Union, and Australia.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] That same year also saw the first inhalable vaccine, developed by Chinese biopharmaceutical company CanSino Biologics.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] High-income countries rapidly bought up vaccines at the start of the pandemic, leading to concerns about vaccine equity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By April 2021, one in 500 people in low and middle-income countries had been vaccinated, compared with one in four in high-income countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] For the first two years of the pandemic, no specific and effective treatment or cure was available.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In 2021, the European Medicines Agency's (EMA) Committee for Medicinal Products for Human Use (CHMP) approved the oral antiviral protease inhibitor, Paxlovid (nirmatrelvir plus the HIV antiviral ritonavir), to treat adult patients.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In these, supportive care includes medication such as paracetamol or NSAIDs to relieve symptoms (fever, body aches, cough), adequate intake of oral fluids and rest.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Good personal hygiene and a healthy diet are also recommended.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Supportive care in severe cases includes treatment to relieve symptoms, fluid therapy, oxygen support and prone positioning, and medications or devices to support other affected vital organs.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] More severe cases may need treatment in hospital.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In those with low oxygen levels, use of the glucocorticoid dexamethasone is recommended to reduce mortality.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Noninvasive ventilation and, ultimately, admission to an intensive care unit for mechanical ventilation may be required to support breathing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) has been used to address the issue of respiratory failure.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Existing drugs such as hydroxychloroquine, lopinavir/ritonavir, and ivermectin are not recommended by US or European health authorities, as there is no good evidence they have any useful effect.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The antiviral remdesivir is available in the US, Canada, Australia, and several other countries, with varying restrictions; however, it is not recommended for use with mechanical ventilation, and is discouraged altogether by the WHO, due to limited evidence of its efficacy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It may take a mild course with few or no symptoms, resembling other common upper respiratory diseases such as the common cold.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In 3–4% of cases (7.4% for those over age 65) symptoms are severe enough to cause hospitalisation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Mild cases typically recover within two weeks, while those with severe or critical diseases may take three to six weeks to recover.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Among those who have died, the time from symptom onset to death has ranged from two to eight weeks.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Prolonged prothrombin time and elevated C-reactive protein levels on admission to the hospital are associated with severe course of COVID-19 and with a transfer to intensive care units (ICU).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Between 5% and 50% of COVID-19 patients experience long COVID, a condition characterised by long-term consequences persisting after the typical convalescence period of the disease.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The most commonly reported clinical presentations are fatigue and memory problems, as well as malaise, headaches, shortness of breath, loss of smell, muscle weakness, low fever and cognitive dysfunction.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many countries attempted to slow or stop the spread of COVID-19 by recommending, mandating or prohibiting behaviour changes, while others relied primarily on providing information.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Measures ranged from public advisories to stringent lockdowns.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Outbreak control strategies are divided into elimination and mitigation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These initial strategies can be pursued sequentially or simultaneously during the acquired immunity phase through natural and vaccine-induced immunity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Containment is undertaken to stop an outbreak from spreading into the general population.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Infected individuals are isolated while they are infectious.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The people they have interacted with are contacted and isolated for long enough to ensure that they are either not infected or no longer contagious.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Screening is the starting point for containment.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Screening is done by checking for symptoms to identify infected individuals, who can then be isolated or offered treatment.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Successful containment or suppression reduces Rt to less than 1.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Should containment fail, efforts focus on mitigation: measures taken to slow the spread and limit its effects on the healthcare system and society.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Successful mitigation delays and decreases the epidemic peak, known as "flattening the epidemic curve".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This decreases the risk of overwhelming health services and provides more time for developing vaccines and treatments.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Individual behaviour changed in many jurisdictions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many people worked from home instead of at their traditional workplaces.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] More drastic actions, such as quarantining entire populations and strict travel bans have been attempted in various jurisdictions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Chinese and Australian government approaches have included many lockdowns and are widely considered the most strict.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The New Zealand government response included the most severe travel restrictions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As part of its K-Quarantine programme, South Korea introduced mass screening and localised quarantines, and issued alerts on the movements of infected individuals.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Singaporean government's response included so-called "circuit breaker lockdowns" and financial support for those affected while also imposing large fines for those who broke quarantine.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Contact tracing attempts to identify recent contacts of newly infected individuals, and to screen them for infection; the traditional approach is to request a list of contacts from infectees, and then telephone or visit the contacts.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Contact tracing was widely used during the Western African Ebola virus epidemic in 2014.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Another approach is to collect location data from mobile devices to identify those who have come in significant contact with infectees, which prompted privacy concerns.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 April 2020, Google and Apple announced an initiative for privacy-preserving contact tracing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In Europe and in the US, Palantir Technologies initially provided COVID-19 tracking services.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] WHO described increasing capacity and adapting healthcare as a fundamental mitigation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic drove widespread adoption of telehealth.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Due to supply chain capacity limitations, some manufacturers began 3D printing material such as nasal swabs and ventilator parts.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In one example, an Italian startup received legal threats due to alleged patent infringement after reverse-engineering and printing one hundred requested ventilator valves overnight.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Individuals and groups of makers created and shared open source designs, and manufacturing devices using locally sourced materials, sewing, and 3D printing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Millions of face shields, protective gowns, and masks were made.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Other ad hoc medical supplies included shoe covers, surgical caps, powered air-purifying respirators, and hand sanitiser.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Novel devices were created such as ear savers, non-invasive ventilation helmets, and ventilator splitters.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In July 2021, several experts expressed concern that achieving herd immunity may not be possible because Delta can transmit among vaccinated individuals.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] CDC published data showing that vaccinated people could transmit Delta, something officials believed was less likely with other variants.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Consequently, WHO and CDC encouraged vaccinated people to continue with non-pharmaceutical interventions such as masking, social distancing, and quarantining if exposed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The outbreak was discovered in Wuhan in November 2019.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It is possible that human-to-human transmission was happening before the discovery.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Based on a retrospective analysis starting from December 2019, the number of cases in Hubei gradually increased, reaching 60 by 20 December and at least 266 by 31 December.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A pneumonia cluster was observed on 26 December and treated by Chinese pulmonologist Zhang Jixian.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] She informed the Wuhan Jianghan CDC on 27 December.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] After analysing pneumonia patient samples, a genetic sequencing company named Vision Medicals reported the discovery of a novel coronavirus to the China CDC (CCDC) on 28 December.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Two days later, a test report from CapitalBio Medlab addressed to the Wuhan Central Hospital reported an erroneous positive result for SARS, causing doctors there to alert authorities.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Eight of those doctors, including ophthalmologist Li Wenliang (1985–2020), were detained by police on 3 January for "spreading false rumours".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] That evening, Wuhan Municipal Health Commission (WMHC) issued a notice about "the treatment of pneumonia of unknown cause".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The next day, WMHC made the announcement public, confirming 27 cases—enough to trigger an investigation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 31 December, the WHO office in China was notified about the cluster of unknown pneumonia cases and immediately launched an investigation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official Chinese sources claimed that the early cases were mostly linked to the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market, which also sold live animals.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In May 2020, CCDC director George Gao initially ruled out the market as a possible origin, as animal samples collected there had tested negative.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 11 January, WHO was notified by the Chinese National Health Commission that the outbreak was associated with exposures in the market, and that China had identified a new type of coronavirus, which it isolated on 7 January.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Initially, the number of cases doubled approximately every seven and a half days.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In early and mid-January, the virus spread to other Chinese provinces, helped by the Chinese New Year migration.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Wuhan was a transport hub and major rail interchange.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 January, the virus' genome was shared publicly.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A retrospective study published in March found that 6,174 people had reported symptoms by 20 January.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A 24 January report indicated human transmission was likely occurring, and recommended personal protective equipment for health workers.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It also advocated testing, given the outbreak's "pandemic potential".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 30 January, 7,818 infections had been confirmed, leading WHO to declare the outbreak a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC), upgrading it to a pandemic on 11 March.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 31 January, the first published modelling study warned of inevitable "independent self-sustaining outbreaks in major cities globally" and called for "large-scale public health interventions".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 31 January, Italy indicated its first confirmed infections had occurred, in two tourists from China.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 19 March, Italy overtook China as the country with the most reported deaths.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 26 March, the United States had overtaken China and Italy as the country with the highest number of confirmed infections.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Genomic analysis indicated that the majority of New York's confirmed infections came from Europe, rather than directly from Asia.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Testing of prior samples revealed a person who was infected in France on 27 December 2019 and a person in the United States who died from the disease on 6 February.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In October, WHO reported that one in ten people around the world may have been infected, or 780 million people, while only 35 million infections had been confirmed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 9 November, Pfizer released trial results for a candidate vaccine, showing a 90 per cent effectiveness in preventing infection.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] That day, Novavax submitted an FDA Fast Track application for their vaccine.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 14 December, Public Health England reported that a variant had been discovered in the UK's southeast, predominantly in Kent.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The variant, later named Alpha, showed changes to the spike protein that could make the virus more infectious.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 13 December, 1,108 infections had been confirmed in the UK.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 4 February 2020, US Secretary of Health and Human Services Alex Azar waived liability for vaccine manufacturers in all cases except those involving "willful misconduct".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 2 January, the Alpha variant, first discovered in the UK, had been identified in 33 countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 6 January, the Gamma variant was first identified in Japanese travellers returning from Brazil.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 29 January, it was reported that the Novavax vaccine was 49 per cent effective against the Beta variant in a clinical trial in South Africa.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The CoronaVac vaccine was reported to be 50.4 per cent effective in a Brazil clinical trial.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 12 March, several countries stopped using the Oxford–AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine due to blood clotting problems, specifically cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (CVST).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 20 March, the WHO and European Medicines Agency found no link to thrombosis, leading several countries to resume administering the vaccine.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In March WHO reported that an animal host was the most likely origin, without ruling out other possibilities.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Delta variant was first identified in India.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In mid-April, the variant was first detected in the UK and two months later it had become a full-fledged third wave in the country, forcing the government to delay reopening that was originally scheduled for June.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 November, Germany advised against the Moderna vaccine for people under 30, due to a possible association with myocarditis.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 24 November, the Omicron variant was detected in South Africa; a few days later the WHO declared it a VoC (variant of concern).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The new variant is more infectious than the Delta variant.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 1 January, Europe passed 100 million cases amidst a surge in the Omicron variant.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Later that month, the WHO recommended the rheumatoid arthritis drug Baricitinib for severe or critical patients.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It also recommended the monoclonal antibody Sotrovimab in patients with non-severe disease, but only those who are at highest risk of hospitalisation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 24 January, the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimated that about 57% of the world's population had been infected by COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 6 March, it was reported that the total worldwide death count had surpassed 6 million people.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 6 July, Omicron subvariants BA.4 and BA.5 had spread worldwide.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] WHO Director-General Tedros Ghebreyesus stated on 14 September 2022, that "[The world has] never been in a better position to end the pandemic", citing the lowest number of weekly reported deaths since March 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] But the end is in sight—we can see the finish line".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 21 October, the United States surpassed 99 million cases of COVID-19, the most cases of any country.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 30 October, the worldwide daily death toll was 424, the lowest since 385 deaths were reported on 12 March 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] 17 November marked the three-year anniversary since health officials in China first detected COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 11 November, the WHO reported that deaths since the month of February had dropped 90 per cent.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Director-General Tedros said this was "cause for optimism".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 3 December, the WHO indicated that, "at least 90% of the world's population has some level of immunity to Sars-CoV-2".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In early December, China began lifting some of its most stringent lockdown measures.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Subsequent data from China's health authorities revealed that 248 million people, nearly 18 per cent of its population, had been infected in the first 20 days of that month.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 29 December, the US joined Italy, Japan, Taiwan and India in requiring negative COVID-19 test results from all people travelling from China due to the new surge in cases.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The EU refused similar measures, stating that the BF7 omicron variant had already spread throughout Europe without becoming dominant.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 4 January 2023, the WHO said the information shared by China during the recent surge in infections lacked data, such as hospitalisation rates.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 January, the WHO's Europe office said the recent viral surge in China posed "no immediate threat." On 16 January, the WHO recommended that China monitor excess mortality to provide "a more comprehensive understanding of the impact of COVID-19".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 30 January, the three-year anniversary of the original declaration, the WHO determined that COVID-19 still met the criteria for a public health emergency of international concern (PHEIC).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 19 March, WHO Director-General Tedros indicated he was "confident" the COVID-19 pandemic would cease to be a public health emergency by the end of the year.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 5 May, the WHO downgraded COVID-19 from being a global health emergency, though it continued to refer to it as a pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO does not make official declarations of when pandemics end.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Tedros agreed, and the WHO reduced the classification to an "established and ongoing health issue".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In a press conference, Tedros remarked that the diminishing threat from COVID-19 had "allowed most countries to return to life as we knew it before COVID-19".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In September the WHO said it had observed "concerning" trends in COVID-19 case numbers and hospitalisations, although analysis was hampered because many countries were no longer recording COVID-19 case statistics.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In November 2023, in response to viral mutations and changing characteristics of infection, the WHO adjusted its treatment guidelines.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Among other changes, remdesivir and molnupiravir were now recommended only for the most severe cases, and deuremidevir and ivermectin were recommended against.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] National reactions ranged from strict lockdowns to public education campaigns.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] WHO recommended that curfews and lockdowns should be short-term measures to reorganise, regroup, rebalance resources, and protect the health care system.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of 26 March 2020, 1.7 billion people worldwide were under some form of lockdown.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This increased to 3.9 billion people by the first week of April—more than half the world's population.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In several countries, protests rose against restrictions such as lockdowns.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A February 2021 study found that protests against restrictions were likely to directly increase the spread of the virus.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of the end of 2021, Asia's peak had come at the same time and at the same level as the world as a whole, in May 2021.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] However, cumulatively they had experienced only half of the global average in cases.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] China opted for containment, instituting strict lockdowns to eliminate viral spread.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The vaccines distributed in China included the BIBP, WIBP, and CoronaVac.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] It was reported on 11 December 2021, that China had vaccinated 1.162 billion of its citizens, or 82.5% of the total population of the country against COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] China's large-scale adoption of zero-COVID had largely contained the first waves of infections of the disease.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] When the waves of infections due to the Omicron variant followed, China was almost alone in pursuing the strategy of zero-Covid to combat the spread of the virus in 2022.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Lockdown continued to be employed in November to combat a new wave of cases; however, protests erupted in cities across China over the country's stringent measures, and in December that year, the country relaxed its zero-COVID policy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first case in India was reported on 30 January 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] India ordered a nationwide lockdown starting 24 March 2020, with a phased unlock beginning 1 June 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Six cities accounted for around half of reported cases—Mumbai, Delhi, Ahmedabad, Chennai, Pune and Kolkata.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Post-lockdown, the Government of India introduced a contact tracking app called Aarogya Setu to help authorities manage contact tracing and vaccine distribution.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] India's vaccination programme was considered to be the world's largest and most successful with over 90% of citizens getting the first dose and another 65% getting the second dose.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A second wave hit India in April 2021, straining healthcare services.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 21 October 2021, it was reported that the country had surpassed 1 billion vaccinations.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Iran reported its first confirmed cases on 19 February 2020, in Qom.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Early measures included the cancellation/closure of concerts and other cultural events, Friday prayers, and school and university campuses.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Iran became a centre of the pandemic in February 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] More than ten countries had traced their outbreaks to Iran by 28 February, indicating a more severe outbreak than the 388 reported cases.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Iranian Parliament closed, after 23 of its 290 members tested positive on 3 March 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] At least twelve sitting or former Iranian politicians and government officials had died by 17 March 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By August 2021, the pandemic's fifth wave peaked, with more than 400 deaths in 1 day.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] COVID-19 was confirmed in South Korea on 20 January 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Military bases were quarantined after tests showed three infected soldiers.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] South Korea introduced what was then considered the world's largest and best-organised screening programme, isolating infected people, and tracing and quarantining contacts.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Screening methods included mandatory self-reporting by new international arrivals through mobile application, combined with drive-through testing, and increasing testing capability to 20,000 people/day.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite some early criticisms, South Korea's programme was considered a success in controlling the outbreak without quarantining entire cities.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic arrived in Europe with its first confirmed case in Bordeaux, France, on 24 January 2020, and subsequently spread widely across the continent.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 17 March 2020, every country in Europe had confirmed a case, and all had reported at least one death, with the exception of Vatican City.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Italy was the first European nation to experience a major outbreak in early 2020, becoming the first country worldwide to introduce a national lockdown.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 13 March 2020, the WHO declared Europe the epicentre of the pandemic and it remained so until the WHO announced it had been overtaken by South America on 22 May.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 18 March 2020, more than 250 million people were in lockdown in Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite deployment of COVID-19 vaccines, Europe became the pandemic's epicentre once again in late 2021.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Italian outbreak began on 31 January 2020, when two Chinese tourists tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 in Rome.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases began to rise sharply, which prompted the government to suspend flights to and from China and declare a state of emergency.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 22 February 2020, the Council of Ministers announced a new decree-law to contain the outbreak, which quarantined more than 50,000 people in northern Italy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 4 March, the Italian government ordered schools and universities closed as Italy reached a hundred deaths.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Sport was suspended completely for at least one month.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 11 March, Italian Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte closed down nearly all commercial activity except supermarkets and pharmacies.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 19 April, the first wave ebbed, as 7-day deaths declined to 433.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 13 October, the Italian government again issued restrictive rules to contain the second wave.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 10 November, Italy surpassed 1 million confirmed infections.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 23 November, it was reported that the second wave of the virus had led some hospitals to stop accepting patients.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The virus was first confirmed to have spread to Spain on 31 January 2020, when a German tourist tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 on La Gomera in the Canary Islands.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Post-hoc genetic analysis has shown that at least 15 strains of the virus had been imported, and community transmission began by mid-February.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 29 March, it was announced that, beginning the following day, all non-essential workers were ordered to remain at home for the next 14 days.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The number of cases increased again in July in a number of cities including Barcelona, Zaragoza and Madrid, which led to reimposition of some restrictions but no national lockdown.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By September 2021, Spain was one of the countries with the highest percentage of its population vaccinated (76% fully vaccinated and 79% with the first dose).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Sweden differed from most other European countries in that it mostly remained open.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Per the Swedish constitution, the Public Health Agency of Sweden has autonomy that prevents political interference and the agency favoured remaining open.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Swedish strategy focused on longer-term measures, based on the assumption that after lockdown the virus would resume spreading, with the same result.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By the end of June, Sweden no longer had excess mortality.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Devolution in the United Kingdom meant that each of its four countries developed its own response.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] England's restrictions were shorter-lived than the others.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The UK government started enforcing social distancing and quarantine measures on 18 March 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 16 March, Prime Minister Boris Johnson advised against non-essential travel and social contact, praising work from home and avoiding venues such as pubs, restaurants, and theatres.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 20 March, the government ordered all leisure establishments to close, and promised to prevent unemployment.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 23 March, Johnson banned gatherings and restricted non-essential travel and outdoor activity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Unlike previous measures, these restrictions were enforceable by police through fines and dispersal of gatherings.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Most non-essential businesses were ordered to close.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 24 April 2020, it was reported that a promising vaccine trial had begun in England; the government pledged more than £50 million towards research.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 16 April 2020, it was reported that the UK would have first access to the Oxford vaccine, due to a prior contract; should the trial be successful, some 30 million doses would be available.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 2 December 2020, the UK became the first developed country to approve the Pfizer vaccine; 800,000 doses were immediately available for use.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In August 2022 it was reported that viral infection cases had declined in the UK.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The virus arrived in the United States on 13 January 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases were reported in all North American countries after Saint Kitts and Nevis confirmed a case on 25 March, and in all North American territories after Bonaire confirmed a case on 16 April.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Per *Our World in Data*, 103,436,829 confirmed cases have been reported in the United States with 1,238,189 deaths, the most of any country, and the nineteenth-highest per capita worldwide.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] COVID-19 is the deadliest pandemic in US history; it was the third-leading cause of death in the US in 2020, behind heart disease and cancer.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] From 2019 to 2020, US life expectancy dropped by 3 years for Hispanic Americans, 2.9 years for African Americans, and 1.2 years for white Americans.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These effects have persisted as US deaths due to COVID-19 in 2021 exceeded those in 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In the United States, COVID-19 vaccines became available under emergency use in December 2020, beginning the national vaccination programme.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first COVID-19 vaccine was officially approved by the Food and Drug Administration on 23 August 2021.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 18 November 2022, while cases in the U.S. had declined, COVID variants BQ.1/BQ.1.1 had become dominant in the country.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In March 2020, as cases of community transmission were confirmed across Canada, all of its provinces and territories declared states of emergency.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Provinces and territories, to varying degrees, implemented school and daycare closures, prohibitions on gatherings, closures of non-essential businesses and restrictions on entry.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Canada severely restricted its border access, barring travellers from all countries with some exceptions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases surged across Canada, notably in the provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, Quebec and Ontario, with the formation of the Atlantic Bubble, a travel-restricted area of the country (formed of the four Atlantic provinces).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Vaccine passports were adopted in all provinces and two of the territories.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Per a report on 11 November 2022, Canadian health authorities saw a surge in influenza, while COVID-19 was expected to rise during winter.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have reached South America on 26 February 2020, when Brazil confirmed a case in São Paulo.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 3 April, all countries and territories in South America had recorded at least one case.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 13 May 2020, it was reported that Latin America and the Caribbean had reported over 400,000 cases of COVID-19 infection with 23,091 deaths.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 22 May 2020, citing the rapid increase of infections in Brazil, the WHO declared South America the epicentre of the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of 16 July 2021, South America had recorded 34,359,631 confirmed cases and 1,047,229 deaths from COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Due to a shortage of testing and medical facilities, it is believed that the outbreak is far larger than the official numbers show.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The virus was confirmed to have spread to Brazil on 25 February 2020, when a man from São Paulo who had travelled to Italy tested positive for the virus.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The disease had spread to every federative unit of Brazil by 21 March.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 19 June 2020, the country reported its one millionth case and nearly 49,000 reported deaths.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] One estimate of under-reporting was 22.62% of total reported COVID-19 mortality in 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of 06 June 2026, Brazil, with 38,024,465 confirmed cases and 703,961 deaths, has the third-highest number of confirmed cases and second-highest death toll from COVID-19 in the world, behind only those of the United States and India.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have spread to Africa on 14 February 2020, with the first confirmed case announced in Egypt.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first confirmed case in sub-Saharan Africa was announced in Nigeria at the end of February 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Within three months, the virus had spread throughout the continent; Lesotho, the last African sovereign state to have remained free of the virus, reported its first case on 13 May 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 26 May, it appeared that most African countries were experiencing community transmission, although testing capacity was limited.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Most of the identified imported cases arrived from Europe and the United States rather than from China where the virus originated.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many preventive measures were implemented by different countries in Africa including travel restrictions, flight cancellations, and event cancellations.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite fears, Africa reported lower death rates than other, more economically developed regions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early June 2021, Africa faced a third wave of COVID infections with cases rising in 14 countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 4 July the continent recorded more than 251,000 new COVID cases, a 20% increase from the prior week and a 12% increase from the January peak.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] More than sixteen African countries, including Malawi and Senegal, recorded an uptick in new cases.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO labelled it Africa's 'Worst Pandemic Week Ever'.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In October 2022, WHO reported that most countries on the African continent will miss the goal of 70 per cent vaccination by the end of 2022.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have reached Oceania on 25 January 2020, with the first confirmed case reported in Melbourne, Australia.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] It has since spread elsewhere in the region.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Australia and New Zealand were praised for their handling of the pandemic in comparison to other Western nations, with New Zealand and each state in Australia wiping out all community transmission of the virus several times even after re-introduction into the community.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As a result of the high transmissibility of the Delta variant, however, by August 2021, the Australian states of New South Wales and Victoria had conceded defeat in their eradication efforts.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early October 2021, New Zealand also abandoned its elimination strategy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In November and December, following vaccination efforts, the remaining states of Australia, excluding Western Australia, voluntarily gave up COVID-Zero to open up state and international borders.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The open borders allowed the Omicron variant of COVID-19 to enter quickly, and cases subsequently exceeded 120,000 a day.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By early March 2022, with cases exceeding 1,000 a day, Western Australia conceded defeat in its eradication strategy and opened its borders.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite record cases, Australian jurisdictions slowly removed restrictions such as close contact isolation, mask wearing, and density limits by April 2022.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 9 September 2022, restrictions were significantly relaxed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The aircraft mask mandate was scrapped nationwide, and daily reporting transitioned to weekly reporting.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 14 September, COVID-19 disaster payment for isolating persons was extended for mandatory isolation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 22 September, all states had ended mask mandates on public transport, including in Victoria, where the mandate had lasted for approximately 800 days.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 30 September 2022, all Australian leaders declared the emergency response finished and announced the end of isolation requirements.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These changes were due in part to high levels of 'hybrid immunity' and low case numbers.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Due to its remoteness and sparse population, Antarctica was the last continent to have confirmed cases of COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first cases were reported in December 2020, almost a year after the first cases of COVID-19 were detected in China.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] At least 36 people were infected in the first outbreak in 2020, with several other outbreaks taking place in 2021 and 2022.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNSC) was criticised for its slow response, especially regarding the UN's global ceasefire, which aimed to open up humanitarian access to conflict zones.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The United Nations Security Council was criticised due to the inadequate manner in which it dealt with the COVID-19 pandemic, namely the poor ability to create international collaboration during this crisis.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 23 March 2020, United Nations Secretary-General António Manuel de Oliveira Guterres appealed for a global ceasefire; 172 UN member states and observers signed a non-binding supporting statement in June, and the UN Security Council passed a resolution supporting it in July.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 29 September 2020, Guterres urged the International Monetary Fund to help certain countries via debt relief and also call for countries to increase contributions to develop vaccines.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO spearheaded initiatives such as the COVID-19 Solidarity Response Fund to raise money for the pandemic response, the UN COVID-19 Supply Chain Task Force, and the solidarity trial for investigating potential treatment options for the disease.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVAX programme, co-led by the WHO, GAVI, and the Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations (CEPI), aimed to accelerate the development, manufacture, and distribution of COVID-19 vaccines, and to guarantee fair and equitable access across the world.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic shook the world's economy, with especially severe economic damage in the United States, Europe and Latin America.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A consensus report by American intelligence agencies in April 2021 concluded, "Efforts to contain and manage the virus have reinforced nationalist trends globally, as some states turned inward to protect their citizens and sometimes cast blame on marginalised groups".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] COVID-19 inflamed partisanship and polarisation around the world as bitter arguments exploded over how to respond.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] International trade was disrupted amid the formation of no-entry enclaves.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic led many countries and regions to impose quarantines, entry bans, or other restrictions, either for citizens, recent travellers to affected areas, or for all travellers.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Travel collapsed worldwide, damaging the travel sector.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The effectiveness of travel restrictions was questioned as the virus spread across the world.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] One study found that travel restrictions only modestly affected the initial spread, unless combined with other infection prevention and control measures.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Researchers concluded that "travel restrictions are most useful in the early and late phase of an epidemic" and "restrictions of travel from Wuhan unfortunately came too late".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The European Union rejected the idea of suspending the Schengen free travel zone.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Several countries repatriated their citizens and diplomatic staff from Wuhan and surrounding areas, primarily through charter flights.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Canada, the United States, Japan, India, Sri Lanka, Australia, France, Argentina, Germany and Thailand were among the first to do so.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Brazil and New Zealand evacuated their own nationals and others.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 14 March, South Africa repatriated 112 South Africans who tested negative, while four who showed symptoms were left behind.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Pakistan declined to evacuate its citizens.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 15 February, the US announced it would evacuate Americans aboard the *Diamond Princess* cruise ship, and on 21 February, Canada evacuated 129 Canadians from the ship.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early March, the Indian government began repatriating its citizens from Iran.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 20 March, the United States began to withdraw some troops from Iraq.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic and responses to it damaged the global economy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 27 February 2020, worries about the outbreak crushed US stock indexes, which posted their sharpest falls since 2008.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Tourism collapsed due to travel restrictions, closing of public places including travel attractions, and advice of governments against travel.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Airlines cancelled flights, while British regional airline Flybe collapsed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The cruise line industry was hard hit, and train stations and ferry ports closed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] International mail stopped or was delayed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The retail sector faced reductions in store hours or closures.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Retailers in Europe and Latin America faced traffic declines of 40 per cent.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] North America and Middle East retailers saw a 50–60 per cent drop.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Shopping centres faced a 33–43 per cent drop in foot traffic in March compared to February.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Mall operators around the world coped by increasing sanitation, installing thermal scanners to check the temperature of shoppers, and cancelling events.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Hundreds of millions of jobs were lost, including more than 40 million jobs in the US.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to a report by Yelp, about 60% of US businesses that closed will stay shut permanently.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The International Labour Organization (ILO) reported that the income generated in the first nine months of 2020 from work across the world dropped by 10.7%, or $3.5 trillion.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Pandemic fears led to panic buying, emptying groceries of essentials such as food, toilet paper, and bottled water.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Panic buying stemmed from perceived threat, perceived scarcity, fear of the unknown, coping behaviour and social psychological factors (e.g. social influence and trust).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Supply shortages were due to disruption to factory and logistic operations; shortages were worsened by supply chain disruptions from factory and port shutdowns, and labour shortages.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Shortages continued as managers underestimated the speed of economic recovery after the initial economic crash.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The technology industry, in particular, warned of delays from underestimates of semiconductor demand for vehicles and other products.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to WHO Secretary-General Tedros Ghebreyesus, demand for personal protective equipment (PPE) rose one hundredfold, pushing prices up twentyfold.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In September 2021, the World Bank reported that food prices remained generally stable and the supply outlook remained positive.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] However, the poorest countries witnessed a sharp increase in food prices, reaching the highest level since the pandemic began.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Agricultural Commodity Price Index stabilised in the third quarter but remained 17% higher than in January 2021.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By contrast, petroleum products were in surplus at the beginning of the pandemic, as demand for gasoline and other products collapsed due to reduced commuting and other trips.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The 2021 global energy crisis was driven by a global surge in demand as the world economy recovered.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Energy demand was particularly strong in Asia.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The performing arts and cultural heritage sectors were profoundly affected by the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Both organisations' and individuals' operations have been impacted globally.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By March 2020, across the world and to varying degrees, museums, libraries, performance venues, and other cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed with their exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A 2021 UNESCO report estimated ten million job losses worldwide in the culture and creative industries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some services continued through digital platforms, such as live streaming concerts or web-based arts festivals.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic affected political systems, causing suspensions of legislative activities, isolations or deaths of politicians, and rescheduled elections.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Although they developed broad support among epidemiologists, NPIs (non-pharmaceutical interventions) were controversial in many countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Intellectual opposition came primarily from other fields, along with heterodox epidemiologists.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic (and the response of Brazilian politicians to it) led to widespread panic, confusion, and pessimism in Brazil.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] When questioned regarding record deaths in the country in April 2020, Brazilian president Jair Bolsonaro said "So what?
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A series of federal health ministers resigned or were dismissed after they refused to implement Bolsonaro's policies.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Disagreements between federal and state governments led to a chaotic and delayed response to the rapid spread of the virus, exacerbated by preexisting social and economic disparities in the country.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Employment, investment and valuation of the Brazilian real plummeted to record lows.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Brazil was also heavily affected by the Delta and Omicron variants.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] At the height of the outbreak in the spring of 2021, 3,000+ Brazilians were dying per day.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Bolsonaro's loss to Lula da Silva in the 2022 presidential election is widely credited to the former's mishandling of the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Multiple provincial-level administrators of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) were dismissed over their handling of quarantine measures.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some commentators claimed this move was intended to protect CCP General Secretary Xi Jinping.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The US intelligence community claimed that China intentionally under-reported its COVID-19 caseload.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Chinese government maintained that it acted swiftly and transparently.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Journalists and activists in China who reported on the pandemic were detained by authorities, including Zhang Zhan, who was arrested and tortured.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early March 2020, the Italian government criticised the EU's lack of solidarity with Italy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 22 March 2020, after a phone call with Italian Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte, Russian president Vladimir Putin ordered the Russian army to send military medics, disinfection vehicles, and other medical equipment to Italy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early April, Norway and EU states like Romania and Austria started to offer help by sending medical personnel and disinfectant, and European Commission president Ursula von der Leyen offered an official apology to the country.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Beginning in mid-April 2020, protestors objected to government-imposed business closures and restrictions on personal movement and assembly.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Simultaneously, essential workers protested unsafe conditions and low wages by participating in a brief general strike.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some political analysts claimed that the pandemic contributed to US President Donald Trump's 2020 defeat to former Vice President Joe Biden and Senator Kamala Harris.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic in the United States prompted calls for the United States to adopt social policies common in other wealthy countries, including universal health care, universal child care, paid sick leave, and higher levels of funding for public health.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Kaiser Family Foundation estimated that preventable hospitalisations of unvaccinated Americans in the second half of 2021 cost US$13.8 billion.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] There were also protest in regards to vaccine mandates in the United States.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In January 2022, the US Supreme Court struck down an OSHA rule that mandated vaccination or a testing regimen for all companies with greater than 100 employees.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The number of journalists imprisoned or detained increased worldwide; some detentions were related to the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The planned NATO "Defender 2020" military exercise in Germany, Poland and the Baltic states, the largest NATO war exercise since the end of the Cold War, was held on a reduced scale.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Iranian government was heavily affected by the virus, which infected some two dozen parliament members and political figures.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Iranian president Hassan Rouhani wrote a public letter to world leaders asking for help on 14 March 2020, due to a lack of access to international markets.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Saudi Arabia, which had launched a military intervention in Yemen in March 2015, declared a ceasefire.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Diplomatic relations between Japan and South Korea worsened.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] South Korea criticised Japan's "ambiguous and passive quarantine efforts" after Japan announced travellers from South Korea must quarantine for two weeks.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] South Korean society was initially polarised on president Moon Jae-in's response to the crisis; many Koreans signed petitions calling for Moon's impeachment or praising his response.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some countries passed emergency legislation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some commentators expressed concern that it could allow governments to strengthen their grip on power.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In Hungary, the parliament voted to allow Prime Minister Viktor Orbán to rule by decree indefinitely, suspend parliament and elections, and punish those deemed to have spread false information.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In countries such as Egypt, Turkey, and Thailand, opposition activists and government critics were arrested for allegedly spreading fake news.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In India, journalists criticising the government's response were arrested or issued warnings by police and authorities.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic disrupted food systems worldwide, hitting at a time when hunger and undernourishment were rising- an estimated 690 million people lacked food security in 2019.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Food access fell – driven by falling incomes, lost remittances, and disruptions to food production.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic and its accompanying lockdowns and travel restrictions slowed movement of food aid.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to the WHO, 811 million people were undernourished in 2020, "likely related to the fallout of COVID-19".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic impacted educational systems in many countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many governments temporarily closed educational institutions, often replaced by online education.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Other countries, such as Sweden, kept their schools open.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of September 2020, approximately 1.077 billion learners were affected due to school closures.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] School closures impacted students, teachers, and families with far-reaching economic and societal consequences.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] They shed light on social and economic issues, including student debt, digital learning, food insecurity, and homelessness, as well as access to childcare, health care, housing, internet, and disability services.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The impact was more severe for disadvantaged children.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many countries, including Bangladesh, granted auto promotion to the public examination candidates.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Higher Education Policy Institute reported that around 63% of students claimed worsened mental health as a result of the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic impacted global health for many conditions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Visits for heart attack symptoms declined by 38% in the US and 40% in Spain.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The head of cardiology at the University of Arizona said, "My worry is some of these people are dying at home because they're too scared to go to the hospital".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] People with strokes and appendicitis were less likely to seek treatment.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Medical supply shortages impacted many people.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic impacted mental health, increasing anxiety, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder, affecting healthcare workers, patients and quarantined individuals.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In late 2022, during the first northern hemisphere autumn and winter seasons following the widespread relaxation of global public health measures, North America and Europe experienced a surge in respiratory viruses and coinfections in both adults and children.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This formed the beginning of the 2022–2023 paediatric care crisis and what some experts termed a "tripledemic" of seasonal influenza, respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), and SARS-CoV-2 throughout North America.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In the United Kingdom, paediatric infections also began to spike beyond pre-pandemic levels, albeit with different illnesses, such as Group A streptococcal infection and resultant scarlet fever.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of mid-December 2022, 19 children in the UK had died due to Strep A and the wave of infections had begun to spread into North America and Mainland Europe.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The B/Yamagata lineage of influenza B might have become extinct in 2020/2021 due to COVID-19 pandemic measures.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] There have been no naturally occurring cases confirmed since March 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In 2023, the WHO concluded that protection against the Yamagata lineage was no longer necessary in the seasonal flu vaccine, reducing the number of lineages targeted by the vaccine from four to three.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Preventative measures taken during the COVID-19 pandemic may have impacted the number of bronchiolitis cases, with observed decreases in cases during the pandemic followed by an increase when preventative measures were rolled back.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic and the reaction to it positively affected the environment and climate as a result of reduced human activity.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the "anthropause", fossil fuel use decreased, resource consumption declined, and waste disposal improved, generating less pollution.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Planned air travel and vehicle transportation declined.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In China, lockdowns and other measures resulted in a 26% decrease in coal consumption, and a 50% reduction in nitrogen oxides emissions.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In 2020, a worldwide study on mammalian wildlife responses to human presence during COVID lockdowns found complex patterns of animal behaviour.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Carnivores were generally less active when humans were around, while herbivores in developed areas were more active.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Among other findings, this suggested that herbivores may view humans as a shield against predators, highlighting the importance of location and human presence history in understanding wildlife responses to changes in human activity in a given area.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A wide variety of largely mammalian species, both captive and wild, have been shown to be susceptible to SARS-CoV-2, with some encountering a particularly high degree of fatal outcomes.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In particular, both farmed and wild mink have developed highly symptomatic and severe COVID-19 infections, with a mortality rate as high as 35–55% according to one study.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] White-tailed deer, on the other hand, have largely avoided severe outcomes but have effectively become natural reservoirs of the virus, with large numbers of free-ranging deer infected throughout the US and Canada, including approximately 80% of Iowa's wild deer herd.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] An August 2023 study appeared to confirm the status of white-tailed deer as a disease reservoir, noting that the viral evolution of SARS-CoV-2 in deer occurs at triple the rate of its evolution in humans and that infection rates remained high, even in areas rarely frequented by humans.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Heightened prejudice, xenophobia, and racism toward people of Chinese and East Asian descent were documented around the world.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Reports from February 2020, when most confirmed cases were confined to China, cited racist sentiments about Chinese people 'deserving' the virus.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Individuals of Asian descent in Europe and North America reported increasing instances of racially motivated abuse and assaults as a result of the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] US president Donald Trump was criticised for referring to SARS-CoV-2 as the "Chinese Virus" and "Kung Flu", terms which were condemned as being racist and xenophobic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Age-based discrimination against older adults increased during the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This was attributed to their perceived vulnerability and subsequent physical and social isolation measures, which, coupled with their reduced social activity, increased dependency on others.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Similarly, limited digital literacy left the elderly more vulnerable to isolation, depression, and loneliness.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] American bioethicist Arthur Caplan responded to Kampf, writing "Criticising [the unvaccinated] who... wind up in hospitals and morgues in huge numbers, put stress on finite resources, and prolong the pandemic... is not stigmatising, it is deserved moral condemnation".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In January 2022, Amnesty International urged Italy to change their anti-COVID-19 restrictions to avoid discrimination against unvaccinated people, saying that "the government must continue to ensure that the entire population can enjoy its fundamental rights".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The restrictions included mandatory vaccination over the age of 50, and mandatory vaccination to use public transport.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic triggered massive changes in behaviour, from increased Internet commerce to cultural changes in the workplace.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Online retailers in the US posted $791.70 billion in sales in 2020, an increase of 32.4% from $598.02 billion the year before.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Home delivery orders increased, while indoor restaurant dining shut down due to lockdown orders or low sales.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Hackers, cybercriminals and scammers took advantage of the changes to launch new online attacks.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Education in some countries temporarily shifted from physical attendance to video conferencing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Massive layoffs shrank the airline, travel, hospitality, and other industries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite most corporations implementing measures to address COVID-19 in the workplace, a poll from Catalyst found that as many as 68% of employees around the world felt that these policies were only performative and "not genuine".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic led to a surge in remote work.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to a Gallup poll, only 4% of US employees were fully remote before the pandemic, compared to 43% in May 2020.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Among white collar workers, that shift was more pronounced, with 6% increasing to 65% in the same period.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] That trend continued in later stages of the pandemic, with many workers choosing to remain remote even after workplaces reopened.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many Nordic, European, and Asian companies increased their recruitment of international remote workers even as the pandemic waned, partially to save on labour costs.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This also led to a talent drain in the global south and in remote areas in the global north.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] High cost of living and dense urban areas also lost office real estate value due to remote worker exodus.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By May 2023, due to increasing layoffs and concerns over productivity, some white collar workplaces in the US had resorted to performance review penalties and indirect incentives (e.g. donations to charity) to encourage workers to return to the office.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A 2021 study noted that the COVID-19 pandemic had increased interest in epidemics and infectious diseases among both historians and the general public.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Prior to the pandemic, these topics were usually overlooked by "general" history and only received attention in the history of medicine.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many comparisons were made between the COVID-19 and 1918 influenza pandemics, including the development of anti-mask movements, the widespread promotion of misinformation and the impact of socioeconomic disparities.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In some areas, religious groups exacerbated the spread of the virus, through large gatherings and the dissemination of misinformation.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some religious leaders decried what they saw as violations of religious freedom.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In other cases, religious identity was a beneficial factor for health, increasing compliance with public health measures and protecting against the negative effects of isolation on mental wellbeing.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some news organisations removed their online paywalls for some or all of their pandemic-related articles and posts.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many scientific publishers provided pandemic-related journal articles to the public free of charge as part of the National Institutes of Health's COVID-19 Public Health Emergency Initiative.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to one estimate from researchers at the University of Rome, 89.5% of COVID-19-related papers were open access, compared to an average of 48.8% for the ten most deadly human diseases.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The share of papers published on preprint servers prior to peer review increased dramatically.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the pandemic, Web GIS technology was leveraged to provide up to date visualisations of data related to the pandemic with the public.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Employing this technology, the Johns Hopkins University COVID-19 dashboard served as the first global visualisation of COVID-19 data, which established it as the default method for government agencies to dissemeniate relevant spatial information.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These dashboards were described by Jonathan Everts as "the most striking cultural artefact of the current coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) pandemic", and during the pandemic every state government in the United States maintained one.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Misinformation and conspiracy theories about the pandemic have been widespread; they travel through mass media, social media and text messaging.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In March 2020, WHO declared an "infodemic" of incorrect information.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cognitive biases, such as confirmation bias, are linked to conspiracy beliefs, including COVID-19 vaccine hesitancy.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic had a major impact on popular culture.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] It was included in the narratives of ongoing pre-pandemic television series and become a central narrative in new ones, with mixed results.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Writing for *The New York Times* about the then-upcoming BBC sitcom *Pandemonium* on 16 December 2020, David Segal asked, "Are we ready to laugh about Covid-19?
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Or rather, is there anything amusing, or recognizable in a humorous way, about life during a plague, with all of its indignities and setbacks, not to mention its rituals and rules".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic had driven some people to seek peaceful escapism in media, while others were drawn towards fictional pandemics (e.g. zombie apocalypses) as an alternate form of escapism.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Common themes have included contagion, isolation and loss of control.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many drew comparisons to the fictional film *Contagion* (2011), praising its accuracies while noting some differences, such as the lack of an orderly vaccine rollout.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As people turned to music to relieve emotions evoked by the pandemic, Spotify listenership showed that classical, ambient and children's genres grew, while pop, country and dance remained relatively stable.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A March 2022 review declared a transition to endemic status to be "inevitable".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In June 2022, an article in *Human Genomics* said that the pandemic was still "raging", but that "now is the time to explore the transition from the pandemic to the endemic phase".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Another review that month predicted that the virus that causes COVID-19 would become the fifth endemic seasonal coronavirus, alongside four other human coronaviruses.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A February 2023 review of the four common cold coronaviruses concluded that the virus would become seasonal and, like the common cold, cause less severe disease for most people.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Another 2023 review stated that the transition to endemic COVID-19 may take years or decades.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 5 May 2023, the WHO declared that the pandemic was no longer a public health emergency of international concern.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This led several media outlets to incorrectly report that this meant the pandemic was "over".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO commented to Full Fact that it was unlikely to declare the pandemic over "in the near future" and mentioned cholera, which it considers to have been a pandemic since 1961 (i.e., continuously for the last 65 years).
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO does not have an official category for pandemics or make declarations of when pandemics start or end.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In June 2023, Hans Kluge, director of the WHO in Europe, commented that "While the international public health emergency may have ended, the pandemic certainly has not".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Epidemics and pandemics usually end when the disease becomes endemic, and when the disease becomes "an accepted, manageable part of normal life in a given society".
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of March 2024, there was no widely agreed definition of when a disease is or is not a pandemic, though efforts at a formal definition were underway.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Experts asked by *Time* that month noted that COVID-19 continued to circulate and cause disease, but expressed uncertainty as to whether it should still be described as a pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In December 2024, Director-General of the World Health Organization Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus stated that COVID should not be referred to in past tense as it is "still with us, still causes acute disease and Long COVID and still kills...
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 2025, five years after the start of the pandemic, experts asked by *The Independent* and *The Washington Post* generally considered COVID-19 to have become endemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases and deaths from COVID-19 still remained high; in the United States, the only two infectious diseases causing more than 10,000 deaths a year were flu and COVID, according to an expert in *The Washington Post*.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite strong economic rebounds following the initial lockdowns in early 2020, towards the latter phases of the pandemic, many countries began to experience long-term economic effects.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Several countries saw high inflation rates which had global impacts, particularly in developing countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some economic impacts such as supply chain and trade operations were seen as more permanent as the pandemic exposed major weaknesses in these systems.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In Australia, the pandemic caused an increase in occupational burnout in 2022.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the pandemic, a large percentage of workers in Canada came to prefer working from home, which had an impact on the traditional work model.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some corporations made efforts to force workers to return to work on-site, while some embraced the idea.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] There was a "travel boom" causing air travel to recover at rates faster than anticipated, and the aviation industry became profitable in 2023 for the first time since 2019, before the pandemic.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] However, economic issues meant some predicted that the boom would begin to slow down.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Business travel on airlines was still below pre-pandemic levels and is predicted not to recover.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] An increase in excess deaths from underlying causes not related to COVID-19 has been largely blamed on systematic issues causing delays in health care and screening during the pandemic, which has resulted in an increase of non-COVID-19 related deaths.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the pandemic, millions of children missed out on vaccinations as countries focused efforts on combating COVID-19.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Efforts were made to increase vaccination rates among children in low-income countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These efforts were successful in increasing vaccination rates for some diseases, though the UN noted that post-pandemic measles vaccinations were still falling behind.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some of the decrease in immunisation was driven by an increase in mistrust of public health officials.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This was seen in both low-income and high-income countries.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Several African countries saw a decline in vaccinations due to misinformation around the pandemic flowing into other areas.
[src:covid-19-pandemic/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Immunisation rates have yet to recover in the United States and the United Kingdom.
